          <p style="color:green">Ready for review. Fact check what we have and describe what is missing.</p> 

            <p>You need to check that your technology or service is secure.</p>

            <h2 id="check-your-controls-are-working">Check your controls are working</h2>

            <p>It is not enough to put your controls in place. You need to check if your controls are working as you expect them to.</p>

            <p>You need to check your controls when you:</p>

            <ul>
              <li>design them</li>
              <li>implement them</li>
              <li>make changes</li>
              <li>discover a new threat</li>
            </ul>

            <p>Consider asking someone outside your team to assess your controls. You can do this as part of your security testing.</p>

            <p>Check <a href="https://www.security.gov.uk/guidance/secure-by-design/activities/assessing-the-effectiveness-of-security-controls" target="_blank">GOV.UK guidance on checking your controls<span class="govuk-visually-hidden"> (opens in a new tab)</span></a>.</p>

          <h2 id="do-security-testing">Do security testing</h2>

          <p>You need to do security testing in all phases of your project. Depending on your context and risk management strategy, this can include:</p>

            <ul>
              <li>automated and manual tests</li>
              <li>penetration testing (pen testing)</li>
              <li>bug bounties</li>
              <li>simulations</li>
            </ul>

          <p>Check <a href="/development/do-security-testing">how to do security testing in Defence</a>. The guidance includes how to ask for support.</p>
            
            <p class="govuk-body govuk-body--secondary govuk-!-font-size-14 govuk-!-margin-top-8 govuk-!-margin-bottom-0"> Published July 2024</p>

          </div>

